Right now your `<p class="lead">` paragraphs inside the “Approach” box use the **same width constraint as the split sections** (`max-width: 68ch`)【21†source】. That keeps them narrower than the centered title. To make those paragraphs take up *approximately the same width as the title* on wider screens (≥ 900 px), you can override that constraint.

Here’s a patch for `assets/css/secondary-maths.css` (page-scoped)【20†source】:

```css
/* ===== PATCH: Widen lead paragraphs in Approach box on desktop ===== */
@media (min-width: 900px) {
  .section--approach .box-body p.lead {
    max-width: none;          /* remove the 68ch clamp */
    width: 100%;              /* fill full card width */
    text-align: center;       /* optional: align like the title */
  }
}
```

### Why this works
- On smaller viewports, your existing responsive scaling still applies (lead shrinks gracefully)【21†source】.  
- At ≥ 900 px, the **title already stretches across the full box width** (capped by the card container at `min(1160px, 86vw)`)【21†source】. The override lets the `<p class="lead">` text match that same span.  
- You can decide whether to keep `text-align: left` or `text-align: center`. If you want a **block-paragraph look**, leave it left; if you want **symmetry with the centered title**, use center.  

### Optional refinements
If you’d prefer not to stretch *all* leads, you can target just the **first and last paragraphs** in that box:

```css
@media (min-width: 900px) {
  .section--approach .box-body p.lead:first-of-type,
  .section--approach .box-body p.lead:last-of-type {
    max-width: none;
    width: 100%;
  }
}
```

This way, if you later add mid-section leads, they won’t be widened by default.

---

Do you want the widened leads to be **center-aligned like the title**, or still **left-aligned but full-width**?

You’re still capped by the **container** (`.approach .box-body`) which we set to `max-width: 68ch`. Even if `p.lead { width:100% }`, it can’t exceed its parent. The title sits **outside** that container, so it appears much wider. The fix is to lift the container cap **only on desktop**, and (optionally) keep lists/regular paragraphs at the readable 68ch.

Add this at the **end** of `assets/css/secondary-maths.css`:

```css
/* ===== PATCH: make Approach leads as wide as the title on desktop ===== */
@media (min-width: 900px) {
  /* Let the content area span the full card width */
  .section--approach .box-body {
    max-width: none;   /* remove the 68ch cap here */
    margin-inline: 0;  /* fill the card */
  }

  /* Keep lists and non-lead paragraphs at a comfy line length */
  .section--approach .box-body > :not(.lead) {
    max-width: 68ch;
    margin-inline: auto;  /* center the narrower blocks */
  }

  /* If you want visual symmetry with the centered title, uncomment: */
  /* .section--approach .box-body p.lead { text-align: center; } */
}
```

Why this works
- Your global split text uses `max-width: 68ch` for readability; we mirrored that for the Approach box earlier. That’s what’s keeping the **lead** as narrow as the list now【21†source】.  
- On ≥900 px, we remove the container cap so **`p.lead` can span the full card width**, which matches the visual span of the centered title. Lists and normal paragraphs stay capped at 68ch so they don’t become too wide【21†source】.  
- Page-scoped CSS here is the right place (this page already links `secondary-maths.css`)【19†source】【20†source】.

If you prefer the leads slightly less than full width (e.g., closer to title but not edge-to-edge), replace `max-width: none` with something like:

```css
.section--approach .box-body { max-width: min(1160px, 86vw); } /* matches your section container width */
```

…and keep the `:not(.lead)` block as-is to retain the 68ch cap for lists/body copy【21†source】.

Your JC page already gives the **Approach** card a 5 px border using `var(--text)` (black in light; white in dark)【39†source】, and your HTML sets `data-theme="light|dark"` on `<html>`, so we can key off that attribute for theme‑aware overrides【40†source】.

Add this **at the end** of `assets/css/jc-maths.css`:

```css
/* ===== PATCH: Approach box border matches list accent by theme ===== */
.section--approach .approach-box {
  /* gentle theme-toggle animation (optional) */
  transition: border-color 0.2s ease;
}

/* Light: dark magenta border (same as list text) */
:root[data-theme="light"] .section--approach .approach-box {
  border-color: #660066; /* dark magenta */
}

/* Dark: bright orange border (same as list text) */
:root[data-theme="dark"] .section--approach .approach-box {
  border-color: #ffbd44; /* bright orange */
}
```

Why this works

- It **keeps your existing 5 px border** and rounded shape; we only override the **color**. Because these rules come **after** `.section--approach .approach-box { border: 5px solid var(--text); }`, they win in the cascade without `!important`【39†source】.
- The selectors are scoped under `:root[data-theme="…"]`, which your page already toggles on load and when the user switches themes【40†source】.

